  <h2>Let's Clear Something Up</h2>

  <p>
    Carbon fibre filament does not make your parts as strong as carbon fibre. I need to say that up front because every week someone asks me to print something in "carbon fibre" expecting it to rival a Formula 1 monocoque. That's not how this works.
  </p>

  <p>
    Carbon fibre filaments are base polymers. PETG, Nylon (PA), PPA, PC, blended with short chopped carbon fibres, typically 10-20% by weight. The fibres add stiffness and dimensional stability. They do not add the kind of tensile strength you get from continuous carbon fibre layup. Different process, different result.
  </p>

  <p>
    Now that we've got that out of the way, let's talk about what these materials actually do well.
  </p>

  <h2>PETG-CF: The Everyday Workhorse</h2>

  <p>
    PETG with carbon fibre is where most people should start. It prints almost as easily as regular PETG, same temperatures, same bed adhesion, but the parts come out stiffer and with much better dimensional accuracy. The carbon fibres reduce warping and shrinkage, which means tighter tolerances on functional parts.
  </p>

  <p>
    I use PETG-CF for brackets, housings, jigs, and fixtures where the part needs to hold its shape under moderate load. It machines well after printing, you can tap threads into it, drill clean holes, sand it smooth. The surface finish is matte and professional-looking without any post-processing.
  </p>

  <p>
    The downside: it's more brittle than plain PETG. You trade impact resistance for stiffness. Don't use it for clips, snap-fits, or anything that needs to flex repeatedly.
  </p>

  <h2>PA-CF: The Step Up</h2>

  <p>
    Nylon carbon fibre. PA6-CF or PA12-CF, is the serious engineering material. It's stiffer than PETG-CF, handles higher temperatures (up to about 120°C continuous for PA6-CF), and has much better chemical resistance. This is what I reach for when parts go near engines, fuel, or saltwater.
  </p>

  <p>
    The catch is that nylon is hygroscopic. It absorbs moisture from the air, and wet nylon prints like garbage, stringing, bubbling, weak layer adhesion. You need a filament dryer running during the print or a sealed dry box feeding the machine. This isn't optional. I've ruined enough rolls to know.
  </p>

  <p>
    PA-CF also needs a hardened steel nozzle. Carbon fibres are abrasive, they'll eat through a brass nozzle in a few hundred grams. A hardened steel or ruby-tipped nozzle is mandatory.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>PA6-CF:</strong> Higher heat resistance, stiffer, but harder to print and more moisture-sensitive</li>
    <li><strong>PA12-CF:</strong> Easier to print, less moisture absorption, slightly lower performance. Good middle ground</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>PPA-CF: The High End</h2>

  <p>
    Polyphthalamide with carbon fibre. This is the material I recommend when people need parts that survive in truly hostile environments. PPA-CF handles continuous temperatures up to 150°C, resists automotive fluids, and maintains stiffness under sustained load better than PA-CF.
  </p>

  <p>
    I've used PPA-CF for under-hood brackets on a project car and for sensor mounts on marine engines. The parts have been in service for months with zero degradation. It's expensive, roughly $80-100 per kilogram, and it requires a printer with an enclosed, heated chamber. But for the right application, nothing else comes close in FDM.
  </p>

  <h2>What Carbon Fibre Filament Won't Do</h2>

  <p>
    Let me be direct about the limitations:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>It won't replace metal</strong> in high-load structural applications. A CF-nylon bracket can replace a plastic bracket, sometimes an aluminum one, but not a steel one</li>
    <li><strong>It won't give you continuous fibre performance.</strong> Chopped fibres add stiffness, not the tensile strength of laid-up carbon sheets</li>
    <li><strong>It won't print on any machine.</strong> You need a hardened nozzle at minimum. For PA-CF and PPA-CF, you need drying capability and ideally a heated chamber</li>
    <li><strong>It won't be cheap.</strong> CF filaments cost 2-4x their non-filled equivalents. Factor that into your quoting</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>My Recommendation</h2>

  <p>
    Start with PETG-CF for general-purpose stiff parts. Move to PA-CF when you need heat or chemical resistance. Use PPA-CF when the application truly demands it and you've got the printer to back it up. Skip CF-PLA entirely, it's marketing, not engineering.
  </p>

  <p>
    And buy a hardened nozzle before your first roll. Not after. Trust me on that one.
  </p>
